{"id":"astro-ph/0610598","submitter":"Boris Gaensicke","authors":"K. Beuermann","title":"Barnes-Evans relations for dwarfs with an application to the\n  determination of distances to cataclysmic variables","comments":"Astronomy & Astrophysics in press, 11 pages","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1051/0004-6361:20065930","report-no":null,"categories":"astro-ph","license":null,"abstract":"  Barnes-Evans type relations provide an empirical relationship between the\nsurface brightness of stars and their color. They are widely used for measuring\nthe distances to stars of known radii, as the Roche-lobe filling secondaries in\ncataclysmic variables (CVs). The calibration of the surface brightness of field\ndwarfs of near-solar metalicity with spectral types A0 to L8 covers all\nsecondary spectral types detectable in CVs and related objects and will aid in\nthe measurement of their distances. The calibrations are based on the radii of\nfield dwarfs measured by the Infrared Flux Method and by interferometry.\nPublished photometry is used and homogenized to the Cousins Rc and Ic and the\nCIT JHK photometric systems. The narrow band surface brightness at 7500A is\nbased on our own and published spectrophotometry. Care is taken to select the\ndwarfs for near-solar metalicity, appropriate to CVs, and to avoid errors\ncaused by unrecognized binarity. Relations are provided for the surface\nbrightness in V, Rc, Ic, J, H, K and in a narrow band at 7500A as functions of\nV-K and of spectral type. The method is tested with selected CVs for which\nindependent information on their distances is available. The observed spread in\nthe radii of early M-dwarfs of given mass or luminosity and its influence on\nthe distance measurements of CVs is discussed. As long as accurate\ntrigonometric parallaxes are not routinely available for a large number of CVs,\nthe surface brightness method remains a reliable means of determining distances\nto CVs in which a spectral signature of the secondary star can be discerned.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 19 Oct 2006 16:15:49 GMT"}],"update_date":"2009-11-11"}
